e="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></td></tr></table><pre itemprop="articleBody"><br /><br />On Sat, 22 Dec 2007, Jeff Garzik wrote:<br />&gt; <br />&gt; But regardless of problems, enabling should be done globally, not per<br />&gt; device...<br /><br />I'm ok with trying the "globally" idea, but it has to be "globally but <br />only if absolutely required".<br /><br />And quite frankly, how do you tell whether it's absolutely required or <br />not?<br /><br />I have an idea: the drivers that really need it will do a "please enable <br />MMCONFIG, because I will need it" thing?<br /><br />Ok?<br /><br />And then, since we *need* such a "pci_enable_mmconfig()" call anyway, why <br />not let the driver give which device it controls too, so that we can print <br />out the information (in case the machine then hangs immediately <br />afterwards), and perhaps - if it is shown to help - only do the MMCONFIG <br />cycles for that particular device?<br /><br />Sounds like a plan?<br /><br />		Linus<br /><br /><br /></pre><div align="center"><div class="shariff" data-services="[&quot;reddit&quot;]" data-theme="grey" data-lang="en" data-backend-url="//shariff.lkml.org/index.php"></div></div></td><td width="32" rowspan="2" class="c" valign="top"><img src="/images/icornerr.gif" width="32" height="32" alt="\" /></td></tr><tr><td align="right" valign="bottom">
